view and suggestions between the two delegates at the conference 
largely reflects the compelling necessity of both the nations to 
come closer to strengthen their bilateral ties in global 
interests. Modern India is viewed by Germans as a very valuable 
strategic partner in economic and scientific development because 
of India's ongoing reform-oriented economic policies aimed at 
liberalization offering one of the biggest markets in Asia. [end 
recording] 
  That was a report from our special correspondent in Bonn. 
  Earlier, Mr. Narasimha Rao held talks with the German 
minister for economic cooperation and development, Mr. 
Carl-Dieter Sprangar, and reaffirmed India's commitment to 
closer cooperation with Germany. Mr. Rao also told German 
leaders that New Delhi is keen on enhanced trade and investment 
flow from Germany. 
  Germany has assured India that it will continue to take a 
neutral stance on the Kashmir issue. Kashmir figured 
prominently in the talks between the prime minister and the 
German leaders in Bonn. Mr. Narasimha Rao explained the 
problems faced by India because of Pakistan's abetment of 
terrorism in Jammu and Kashmir and Punjab. He said, Pakistan is 
deliberately creating conditions to obstruct a meaningful 
dialogue. 

</TEXT>

